&quot;The last time religion ruled the world it was known as the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Dark Ages</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.&quot;</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 101<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/9/03 9:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=51.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_mad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: never been sure</span><hr size=1> Unless the reference was directly to the Shir'ah (sp?) Islamic law then turning to the middle east is not necessarily something Kate need address. The difference in laws in Islamic countries about dress, women's conduct and even their ability to participate in careers/cinema/government vary widely.<br>
<br>
I would say though that there's a fundamental point here worth looking at. I often hear tough talk from people about cracking down on this or that or making more stringent laws. Every law we make is a compromise on civil liberty--one we would probably all agree is necessary, but for this reason needs to be watched with a careful eye. We could put tracking chips in the arms of every person at birth, video tape all public movements, transportations, financial transactions and even who sees what movie, buys what CDs etc. and institute a curfew for all citizens at 9pm every night and this would DEFINITELY reduce crime. It would also be a sort of crime in intself and chip away to such a degree our individual freedom and civil rights the end result would be disastrous. <br>
<br>
Security vs. personal freedom. This actually brings us full circle to our Leviation conversation about the social contract. Regardless of the existence of a deity, we must all decide to what degree we will live in the natural vs. governed state. This is an argument from a purely practical position of course and has nothing to do with holy laws or morality--though those can also be made in relation to the law. We don't live in a Nazi state because the resulting security would be useless in this sort of prison world and we would be at just as much risk of being arbitrarily picked up by the thought police and never seen again as being robbed or murdered in a democracy. <br>
<br>
Who do you trust more? Who decides these harsh laws? Who executes them? Who defends the accused? Who ensures there are checks and balances or that a coup won't place a madman in power?<br>
<br>
