<br>
If someone were to ask me would I like to have a legal system like what they have in any Middle Eastern country, I'd say no.. if they asked me if I'd like to live under the Shariah in the context of a proper Islamic state (i.e., Caliphate) I'd say yes.<br>
<br>
The problem with most of the countries over there is that they have stagnated from a fiqh (Islamic jurisprudence) standpoint.  They use as precendent events and rulings from centuries ago, which personally I (and many other actual scholars) think is wrong, but the Muslim world as a whole has become so sheepish.. I don't know if it's fear, or culturalism, or what, but they feel so threatened when you talk about reinterpreting Islamic law to fit our world... even in the years after the death of Prophet Muhammad, the Caliphs would &quot;adjust&quot; the rulings to suit the situation, for example the Caliph Umar, who is considered the second of the &quot;Rightly Guided&quot; caliphs, suspended the whole cutting of the hand for stealing because of a paucity in foodstuffs and enduring hardship -- it's ridiculous to impose that ruling when people are struggling to survive.  These days if anyone made that kind of suggestion some Mullah somewhere would issue a fatwa calling for his/her head.<br>
<br>
Some of these things are so ingrained in people, they just can't let it go.  I'm a big stickler for women's rights in Islam, and I even have to fight my own Muslim sisters on many issues.. many who are brought up overseas are so cemented in their positions, if you try to shift them -- even when it is advocated by the Shari'ah -- you get called a Western feminist trying to infiltrate Islam.. it's pathetic.<br>
<br>
Anyway, that goes a bit off topic, but in a nutshell, I wouldn't want to have the legal standards of a Middle Eastern country applied here.<br>
<br>
