<br>
Well I think part of the issue here is to maintain the level of trueness to Islam.. Adjust, yes, but within parameters.  Some may fear a total loss of Islam to &quot;progress&quot;, but I think we really need to re-think ourselves.. not to &quot;change the law&quot; but to use the law as it was intended -- a fluid structure that shifts and molds to suit any environment.  We want to avoid what we perceive as having happened to the Christian and Jewish communities, which is a gradual moving away from the fundamental belief in the Oneness of God (and all that entails, which is substantial) and our submission to Him.<br>
<br>
I think a lot of Muslims have bought into this whole western = modern = better.  We constantly feel this need to define ourselves according to the west, or to justify/defend ourselves according to the western models of faith, economics, political structure, etc.  What we need to do is gain confidence in ourselves, and think outside the box.  A really thought-provoking book I read on these issues recently is by Tariq Ramadan called &quot;Islam, the West and the Challenges of Modernity&quot;.  An intellectual read, but very good I thought.<br>
<br>
Kate <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=filfilksq>filfilksq</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/11/03 10:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=51.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_mad.gif" align=absmiddle>  oops!</span><hr size=1> &quot;They use as precendent events and rulings from centuries ago, which personally I (and many other actual scholars) think is wrong&quot;<br>
