<br>
BTW, I think the concept of modernizing Islam is an interesting one.  I think I understand why Muslims feel that Christianity and Judaism are not the best role models for modernization.  I suppose that when your life is too secularized with modern day advances, then it is easy to forget about the roots of your religion.  I am currently reading a book written by an Orthodox rabbi(yes, a far cry from the Shermer book I just read), and in his chapter on idolatry he discusses how people are pretty much focusing on objects and achievements and getting away from spirituality and feeling one with God.  I don't share his views on God and religion, but I do find the concept interesting.  Many Orthodox Jews feel the same way about modernizing as Muslims do, and that is why you could usually spot one a mile away.  I do think that the Middle Eastern societies need a huge overhaul right now, but it would be nice if the overhaul could occur while sticking to the roots of their culture.  Islam was the most prosperous culture at one point in time, and they were able to do so without compromising their faith.  I guess that in all this rambling I should just ask Kate, or anyone else who might know, if Muslims are looking back to this prosperous time to see how they could modernize for the future without compromising their religion?  Of course, that might be a topic for another thread...<br>
